<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="238" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="238">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[118,390,398,417]" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">NBP/NIS material examined.</emphasis>
13 ♂, 7 ♀ from Manitoba: Churchill (vi–vii.1962; vii–viii.1961; vi.1967; vii.1969) (CNC).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="239" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="238">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[155,262,454,473]" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[274,480,454,473]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis box="[274,480,454,473]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">Prochyliza brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widespread Nearctic species (Melander 1924; Steyskal 1965; McAlpine 1977). The NIS specimens extend the known range of 
<taxonomicName box="[689,810,482,501]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis box="[689,810,482,501]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">P. brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
northeast.
</paragraph>
<paragraph box="[118,458,567,586]" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">
<heading bold="true" box="[118,458,567,586]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" reason="0">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[118,458,567,586]" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">Diversity and distribution patterns</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="238">
A total of 960 specimens was collected by the NBP and NIS at the 12 sites in the boreal, subarctic and high arctic ecozones. There were distinct latitudinal patterns in diversity across the three ecozones (
<figureCitation box="[891,955,650,669]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="9.[118,195,1460,1477]" captionTargetBox="[121,1119,798,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[118,1122,794,1443]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 12. Number of specimens of Piophilidae species collected by the Northern Biodiversity Program and Northern Insect Survey at 12 study sites in three northern Canadian ecozones: high arctic (white), subarctic (gray), boreal (black). Note break in X-axis." pageId="9" pageNumber="238">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="238">
Abundance and species richness of 
<taxonomicName box="[465,564,678,697]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Piophilidae</taxonomicName>
were lowest in the boreal sites. Only 13 specimens representing five species were collected (
<emphasis box="[371,971,706,725]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">
<taxonomicName box="[371,547,706,725]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Liopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varipes">Liopiophila varipes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[557,759,706,725]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Parapiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrifrons">Parapiophila atrifrons</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[769,844,706,725]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Parapiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dudai">P. dudai</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[854,971,706,725]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Parapiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="penicillata">P. penicillata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[983,1109,706,725]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Parapiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xanthopoda">
<emphasis box="[983,1109,706,725]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">P. xanthopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). All species collected in the boreal were also collected in the subarctic (
<figureCitation box="[738,803,734,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="9.[118,195,1460,1477]" captionTargetBox="[121,1119,798,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[118,1122,794,1443]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 12. Number of specimens of Piophilidae species collected by the Northern Biodiversity Program and Northern Insect Survey at 12 study sites in three northern Canadian ecozones: high arctic (white), subarctic (gray), boreal (black). Note break in X-axis." pageId="9" pageNumber="238">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="9" pageNumber="238" targetBox="[121,1119,798,1438]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="238">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[118,224,1460,1477]" pageId="9" pageNumber="238">FIGURE 12.</emphasis>
Number of specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[428,518,1460,1477]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Piophilidae</taxonomicName>
species collected by the Northern Biodiversity Program and Northern Insect Survey at 12 study sites in three northern Canadian ecozones: high arctic (white), subarctic (gray), boreal (black). Note break in X-axis.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
In contrast, species richness of 
<taxonomicName box="[426,526,118,137]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Piophilidae</taxonomicName>
was highest at the subarctic sites. All but one species (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Arctopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigerrima">Arctopiophila nigerrima</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) were collected in the subarctic ecozone. Some species collected in multiple ecozones were much more abundant in the subarctic sites (e.g., 
<emphasis box="[434,1028,175,193]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[434,607,175,193]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Liopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varipes">Liopiophila varipes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[615,805,175,193]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Neopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setaluna">Neopiophila setaluna</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[813,1028,175,193]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Parapiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="penicillata">Parapiophila penicillata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1047,1111,175,194]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="9.[118,195,1460,1477]" captionTargetBox="[121,1119,798,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[118,1122,794,1443]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 12. Number of specimens of Piophilidae species collected by the Northern Biodiversity Program and Northern Insect Survey at 12 study sites in three northern Canadian ecozones: high arctic (white), subarctic (gray), boreal (black). Note break in X-axis." pageId="10" pageNumber="239">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Although 
<emphasis box="[208,397,203,222]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[208,397,203,222]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Actenoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hilarella">Actenoptera hilarella</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was collected only in subarctic sites in this study, published records (McAlpine 1977) show that it is more widespread in the Nearctic, although rarely collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[155,255,259,278]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Piophilidae</taxonomicName>
were most abundant at the high arctic sites (701 specimens), but species richness was low. Five species were collected: 
<emphasis box="[323,1122,287,306]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[323,513,287,306]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Arctopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arctica">Arctopiophila arctica</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[521,736,287,306]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Arctopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigerrima">Arctopiophila nigerrima</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[744,926,287,306]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Lasiopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">Lasiopiophila pilosa</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[935,1122,287,306]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Neopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setaluna">Neopiophila setaluna</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[155,354,315,334]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[155,354,315,334]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Parapiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulviceps">Parapiophila fulviceps</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[365,578,315,334]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[365,578,315,334]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Arctopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigerrima">Arctopiophila nigerrima</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was collected only at high arctic sites and 
<emphasis box="[950,1035,316,334]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[950,1035,316,334]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Arctopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arctica">A. arctica</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1046,1122,315,334]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[1046,1122,315,334]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Lasiopiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">L. pilosa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[157,258,343,362]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName box="[157,258,343,362]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Parapiophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulviceps">P. fulviceps</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
were much more abundant at high arctic than subarctic sites (
<figureCitation box="[822,888,343,362]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="9.[118,195,1460,1477]" captionTargetBox="[121,1119,798,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[118,1122,794,1443]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 12. Number of specimens of Piophilidae species collected by the Northern Biodiversity Program and Northern Insect Survey at 12 study sites in three northern Canadian ecozones: high arctic (white), subarctic (gray), boreal (black). Note break in X-axis." pageId="10" pageNumber="239">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). The dominance of these species in the high arctic suggests that they may be particularly well-adapted to the harsh conditions on the arctic islands (Downes 1962; McAlpine 1965), although a better understanding of their ecology would be required to identify those adaptations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="239">
Half of the recorded Nearctic species of 
<taxonomicName box="[532,631,456,475]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Piophilidae</taxonomicName>
were identified in the 12 sites sampled in this study, including a new, widespread Holarctic species, and two new North American records. We are aware of additional, undescribed species from other northern sites. A taxonomic revision of Nearctic 
<taxonomicName box="[822,921,512,531]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Piophilidae</taxonomicName>
is ongoing, which will allow for a more comprehensive analysis of geographic patterns of diversity.
</paragraph>
